nodes.bodyText: I always go with lowercase variable names since they're not really immutable
Yup.  Copy/Paste error.  Fixed!
This should describe what operations it does so that it's more clear which data is removed.
Yup.  As I mentioned in my high-level comment I'm going to re-describe the tool to confirm explicitly to the guidance we were given.
if the default is true you should probably invert the argument

Sounds good.  I was wondering about this - in the past I've had to change variable names because they had "not" or similar in their names.
I'll update it.
I think this chain of ifs should be a switch statement instead, it would be clear and maybe faster that way.  (Intellij will do that change automatically for you if you ask it nicely).
Works for me.  I use switch statements so rarely I tend not to think of them.
Fixed!
The S case and the EQ case are identical and should be collapsed together.
Good catch!  Fixed!
typo.  se teh
Fixed!

If we really want this to be anonymizing we should really set it to a random value from a distribution that looks like the surrounding qualities or something along those lines.  It might need to be pretty sophisticated to really remove all information (the bqsr model might be a good starting point.)
Yeah.  My scope for the tool was too overreaching.  By the rules handed down to us, we just need to change the bases that do not match the reference back to reference bases.

By using ALLOW_ALL_READS you're letting in reads that will crash this tool.  You need to either add back the filters:
VALID_ALIGNMENT_START, VALID_ALIGNMENT_END,  alignmentAgreesWithHeader, HAS_MATCHING_BASES_AND_QUALS, READLENGTH_EQUALS_CIGARLENGTH, and SEQ_IS_STORED
or make the tool handle discrepancies in these values.
You should filter out every unmapped read because they contain identifying kmers which cannot be corrected.

You might want to filter everything aligned to alt contigs since their presence probably has identifying information about ethnicity.  Similarly you probably need to remove anything related to HLA.  You might also need to censor all of the MHC as well on chr6 since you can probably infer some information about HLA type from the coverage there.  I don't know how careful you have to be.  There may be other sites where coverage provides a strong identifying signal as well.
Good point.  I'll update the filter to include those, as well as the unmapped reads.  I'm not going to add in any other filtering since that was not the guidance we were given.
Intellij says this condition is always true
Yup.  I missed that warning.  If statement removed.

I think you need to remove all the tags from the reads as well as clean the header.  The tags contain a lot of information which could potentially be identifying (they include for instance an array saying what all the mismatching bases are and where they are...). The header could easily include personal information as well.
I'm not sure how strict you have to be about anonymizing things.
You might want to strip readnames as well.  Most people don't put the sample name in them probably, but you never know...

I'll strip the tags (except for the read group).
I'm not going to sanitize the header or the readnames - per the instructions I was given this isn't necessary.
You should remove all but chr1 and 2 from the header here just for ease of looking at these files. (and from the other one)

nodes.bodyText: this comment isn't quite right since the quality isn't necessarily max
Ah.  Yeah - we just always use 60 as our max.  It's a parameter now anyway so it's inaccurate for two reasons.

I might make this experimental instead of beta.  It seems like a very one-off sort of thing that isn't generally useful, since reads that have all the sequencing data removed are not a particularly in demand resources...
nodes.diffHunk:
@@ -27,7 +29,20 @@
 /**
  * Replace bases in reads with reference bases.
  *
- * Used to sanitize data from samples for the purposes of eliminating Personal Identifiable Information.
+ * Used to anonymize reads with information from the reference.
+ * This tool is useful in the case where you want to use data for analysis,
+ * but cannot publish the data without anonymizing the sequence information.
+ *
+ * Reads are processed, then emitted in a new file.  For a read to be processed
+ * it must have valid start/end positions, sequence information, and consistent
+ * lengths between the sequence, base qualities, and CIGAR string.  In addition
+ * reads must be consistent with the read file header's sequence dictionary.
+ *
+ * For each aligned read, any base that does not match the reference is transformed
+ * to the reference base.  For any transformed bases, the quality is set to a constant
+ * value ({@link #refQual}).  For bases not transformed, the quality is preserved.
+ * Reads transformed in this way also have their CIGARs rewritten to match the new
+ * sequence information.
  */
 @DocumentedFeature
 @BetaFeature
